ABC Corp. is formalized and centralized. Formalization measures an organization's rules, processes, and job descriptions. ABC Corp.'s processes are well-documented, and each employee's job description is established. Centralization is the extent to which an organization's leadership makes decisions. The CEO of ABC Corp. reports to a few supervisors, and low-level workers have minimal decision-making power. Centralization is high. ABC Corp. has a highly formalized and centralized decision-making procedure. The company's steady atmosphere and selling one product to other enterprises may explain this. The corporation controls its operations and processes with a limited staff and a CEO who makes all decisions. 